steroids \u2192 cortisol \u2192 thyroxine","Thyroxine \u2192 sex steroids \u2192 cortisol","Sex steroids \u2192 thyroxine \u2192 cortisol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence for hormone replacement in hypopituitarism is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecortisol\u003C/strong\u003E first, followed by \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E, and finally \u003Cstrong\u003Esex steroids\u003C/strong\u003E. This order is critical for patient safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECortisol must be replaced first because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt prevents potentially fatal adrenal crisis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is essential for cardiovascular stability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is required for proper thyroid hormone metabolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroxine is replaced second because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid replacement without adequate cortisol can precipitate an adrenal crisis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid hormones increase metabolic rate and cortisol requirements\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESex steroids are replaced last as they are not immediately essential for survival.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cortisol replacement must be initiated first in hypopituitarism to prevent adrenal crisis","Thyroid replacement is given second as cortisol is needed for thyroid hormone metabolism","Sex hormone replacement is given last as it is least critical for immediate survival"],"references":["Kim SY. Diagnosis and Treatment of Hypopituitarism. Endocrinol Metab (Seoul). 2015 Dec;30(4):443-55. doi: 10.3803/EnM.2015.30.4.443. PMID: 26790380; PMCID: PMC4722397.","Beysel S, \u00c7ali\u015fkan M, Kizilg\u00fcl M, Kan S, \u00d6zbek M, \u00c7akal E. Clinical evaluation of pituitary insufficiency in adult population. Turk J Med Sci. 2020 Jun 23;50(4):917-921. doi: 10.3906/sag-1908-19. PMID: 32283895; PMCID: PMC7379402."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56635"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15618"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56635"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T15:51:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T15:51:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71164"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"created